                <head>334. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 16, 1963, President Johnson approved the Foreign Assistance Act of
                    1963 (P.L. 88-205; 77 Stat. 379), which, among other things, authorized the
                    President to continue most-favored-nation tariffs on imports from Poland and
                    Yugoslavia. Section 231 of the Trade Expansion Act of 1962 (P.L. 87-794,
                    approved on October 11, 1962; 76 Stat. 872) had required the denial of such
                    tariffs to products of Communist countries, “as soon as practicable.” This had
                    not yet been done.</p>
            </div>
